scopeContent.description:
Photograph of cylinder of Nabonidus, King of Babylonia, inscribed with an account of his building operations and of the chief events of his reign. He describes how he built the temple of the Sun-god at Sippar, and in the course of the work he found an inscription of Naram-Sin, the son of Sargon I, the original founder of the temple, which for 3,200 years had not been seen. From this statement the date of Naram-Sin may be fixed at BC 3750 (No 91,109). In the British Museum'. No copy of photograph annexed to form.

Photograph of tablet containing a copy of an inscription of Tukulti-Nibib, King of Assyria, about BC 1,300, made by the order of Sennacherib. The original was inscribed on a cylinder seal of lapis-lazuli, which was brought by Sennacherib from Babylon, whither it was carried 600 years before, (H 2,673). Letter from Sennacherib, King of Assyria, referring to certain objects given by him to his son Esarhaddon. The tablet is generally known as the 'Will of Sennacherib', (No 1,620). In the British Museum'. No copy of photograph annexed to form.

scopeContent.description:
